26679234-bc78-4ba9-837a-ccf61c4b1d63	Qlub Closes $30 Million Round 	Article	\N	Abu Dhabi SME Hub	Published	2025-10-10 00:00:00+00	<p>Qlub is a contactless dining payment platform that enables&nbsp;diners to instantly view menus, order, and pay via smartphone.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Qlub, the ultra-fast payment system in restaurants, has become ubiquitous across Dubai’s vibrant dining scene. Following its runaway success in the UAE, Qlub has announced the closure of a $30 million funding round to take its smart dining experience global. The round was co-led by the region’s leading alternative investment firm, Shorooq, and Cherry Ventures, with major backing from strategic partners including e&amp;, Mubadala Investments, and Legend Capital.</p><p>This latest funding round underscores the growing demand for seamless, technology-driven dining experiences and positions Qlub to accelerate its global expansion, enhance its product offerings, and further integrate its solutions into the hospitality ecosystem.</p><blockquote><p>"From the very beginning, we saw in Qlub more than just a payments solution—we saw a new infrastructure for how hospitality should work in a digital-first world. Eyad and Mahmoud and the team have consistently proven that they can blend product innovation with deep market understanding, unlocking new behaviour at the intersection of tech and experience,"&nbsp;</p></blockquote><p>noted Mahmoud Adi, Founding Partner at Shorooq.&nbsp;</p><blockquote><p>"We are proud to have backed Qlub from the earliest days and remain committed to supporting visionary companies redefining everyday moments across emerging markets."</p></blockquote><p>Founded in 2021 by Eyad Alkassar and Mahmoud Fouz, Qlub has rapidly emerged as a pioneer in the contactless payment space, offering QR-based solutions that allow diners to view menus, place orders, and settle bills seamlessly using their smartphones. By eliminating the need for physical menus and traditional payment methods, Qlub enhances operational efficiency for restaurants and provides a frictionless experience for customers.</p><p>With a presence in thousands of establishments across many markets, including the UAE, Saudi Arabia, Singapore, Hong Kong, Australia, Brazil, Qatar, Kuwait, and Korea, Qlub has demonstrated significant traction in diverse markets. It is now processing a few billion USD annually and serves millions of customers on a monthly basis, making it the leading QR payment solution for restaurants globally.</p><p>Notable clients include Paul Cafe, Wagamama, Sushi Samba, and La Petite Maison (LPM), where the implementation of Qlub's solutions has led to strong improvements in customer satisfaction and operational efficiency. Qlub clients report a 300% increase in tips, a sevenfold increase in positive Google reviews, an 80% reduction in checkout line by streamlining the process, reducing labour costs, and decreasing the number of required cashiers by an average of a third, and an overall improvement in space utilisation by minimising the need for multiple cashier counters.</p><blockquote><p>"From day one, Qlub has shown how technology can simplify and modernise hospitality. We backed them at seed and are thrilled to support them again as they scale their solution globally and change how restaurants operate,"&nbsp;</p></blockquote><p>added Filip Dames, Founding Partner of Cherry Ventures.&nbsp;</p><blockquote><p>"We look forward to supporting their continued success."</p></blockquote><p>The participation of industry leaders such as e&amp; and Mubadala Investments in this funding round reflects the strategic importance of Qlub's solutions in the evolving landscape of the hospitality industry.</p><blockquote><p>"Qlub's innovative approach to enhancing the dining experience aligns with our commitment to supporting digital transformation in the region,"&nbsp;</p></blockquote><p>said Khalifa Alshamsi, CEO of e&amp; Life.&nbsp;</p><blockquote><p>"We are excited to partner with Qlub as they continue to redefine the standards of service in the hospitality sector."</p></blockquote><p>With the new funding, Qlub plans to:</p><ul><li>Expand its presence in existing markets and enter new regions.</li><li>Enhance its product offerings by integrating advanced analytics and insights to provide restaurants with a deeper understanding of customer behavior and preferences.</li><li>Strengthen partnerships with key players in the hospitality and technology sectors to drive further innovation and adoption of contactless payment solutions.</li></ul><blockquote><p>“Our vision is simple: Qlub makes paying at restaurants ten times faster—and that elevates the entire dining experience,”</p></blockquote><p>&nbsp;said Eyad Alkassar, co-founder and co-CEO of Qlub.&nbsp;</p><blockquote><p>“Why would any restaurant, anywhere in the world, choose to operate without it?"</p><p>“We’re thrilled to have the support of investors, both new and existing partners, as we continue to build Qlub’s vision,”&nbsp;</p></blockquote><p>said Mahmoud Fouz, co-founder and co-CEO of Qlub.&nbsp;</p><blockquote><p>“We’re grateful for the confidence our investors have placed in us and excited for what lies ahead."</p></blockquote>		{Launch}	https://startuprise.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/Qlub-Secures-30-Million-in-New-Funding-Round.webp	0	0	{"byline": "Abu Dhabi SME Hub", "author_bio": null, "author_org": null, "author_name": "Abu Dhabi SME Hub", "author_title": null, "author_photo_url": null}	\N	2025-10-10 05:58:08.825+00	2025-11-13 06:48:20.52987+00	\N	\N	https://startuprise.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/07/Qlub-Secures-30-Million-in-New-Funding-Round.webp	\N	\N	0	{"likes": 0, "views": 0, "comments": 0}	\N	\N	qlub-closes-30-million-round	\N	{}	f	\N	\N	{}	\N	\N	\N	{}	\N	\N	\N	\N	0	0	\N
c076f0a9-b263-4068-b4de-de3514f712a0	How AI and Digital Tools Are Transforming SMEs in Abu Dhabi	Article	\N	\N	Published	2025-10-02 06:52:51.781+00	<p>The emergence of artificial intelligence (AI) and digital tools is reshaping the landscape of small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) worldwide. In Abu Dhabi, a city known for its forward-thinking policies and rapid economic transformation, these technological advancements are not merely trends—they are the driving force behind the next wave of SME evolution. While larger corporations have long benefited from AI and digital tools, SMEs in Abu Dhabi are now starting to realize the immense potential of these technologies in driving innovation, improving efficiency, and scaling operations. AI and digital tools are no longer just “nice-to-have” for SMEs—they are strategic imperatives for staying competitive in an increasingly globalized and tech-driven market. Yet, as transformative as these tools are, the real question is: </p><blockquote><p>How are SMEs in Abu Dhabi truly harnessing these innovations?</p></blockquote><p>In this article, we explore how AI and digital tools are not just enhancing the capabilities of SMEs but fundamentally transforming the way they operate, innovate, and grow. AI: A Game Changer for SME Operations At its core, artificial intelligence has the power to automate mundane tasks, freeing up valuable time for SMEs to focus on more strategic initiatives. From customer service to inventory management, AI is enhancing operational efficiency in ways that were once thought impossible for small businesses. In Abu Dhabi, where the demand for innovation is ever-growing, SMEs are leveraging AI to optimize business processes and make smarter, data-driven decisions. </p><p>However, the real value of AI for SMEs lies in its ability to uncover hidden insights and drive business innovation. By processing vast amounts of data, AI can help businesses identify new market opportunities, predict customer behavior, and tailor services to meet individual needs. Machine learning algorithms can analyze purchasing patterns, identify emerging trends, and even provide predictive maintenance for machinery—helping businesses avoid costly downtime. But AI's role isn't confined to operational tasks; it is also empowering decision-makers in Abu Dhabi's SMEs to make better, faster, and more accurate decisions. AI is a powerful tool that offers businesses the ability to run what-if analyses, forecast trends, and evaluate risks with a level of accuracy and speed that was previously unimaginable. Digital Tools: The Bridge to Seamless Integration Alongside AI, a suite of digital tools is transforming how SMEs in Abu Dhabi interact with customers, manage internal processes, and collaborate with partners. Tools like cloud-based platforms, Customer Relationship Management (CRM) software, and Project Management tools are central to this shift. They not only improve productivity but also enable greater flexibility and scalability for SMEs, allowing them to compete on a global scale. Consider cloud technology, for example. By enabling businesses to store data and run applications over the internet, SMEs can significantly reduce their infrastructure costs while gaining access to scalable, on-demand computing resources. This democratization of technology allows businesses to access enterprise-level tools without the high upfront investment, leveling the playing field for smaller players in the market. </p><p>Moreover, the integration of CRM tools and digital marketing platforms is enabling SMEs to streamline their sales and marketing operations. With these tools, SMEs can engage customers more effectively by leveraging data to personalize marketing campaigns, improve lead generation, and enhance customer experiences. Whether it’s through targeted email campaigns or social media automation, digital tools allow SMEs to run smarter, more efficient marketing campaigns that produce measurable results. The Digital Transformation: Rethinking the SME Business Model As AI and digital tools reshape the operational landscape, SMEs in Abu Dhabi are also rethinking their business models. Traditional models—focused on linear production and customer interactions—are being replaced with agile, data-driven approaches that are far more responsive to market dynamics. For instance, consider the growing adoption of e-commerce platforms and digital marketplaces by SMEs. </p><p>In Abu Dhabi, many businesses that once relied on physical storefronts or traditional sales channels are now engaging customers directly through online platforms. This shift not only expands their customer base but also allows them to access new revenue streams and optimize their supply chains using real-time data. Further, AI-driven predictive analytics is enabling SMEs to forecast demand, manage inventory efficiently, and minimize waste. This is particularly important for industries like retail, manufacturing, and logistics, where demand fluctuations can directly affect profitability. By anticipating future demand with precision, SMEs can reduce costs and improve service delivery, leading to higher customer satisfaction and increased profitability. </p><p>Yet, the broader shift is a rethinking of the value proposition of SMEs. Digital tools and AI aren’t just helping businesses do what they do more efficiently—they are enabling SMEs to create new business models and deliver value in entirely novel ways. Businesses are no longer restricted by their geographical location or traditional business models. In the case of Abu Dhabi, this means that SMEs can expand globally and provide services across borders without being constrained by physical limitations. Overcoming Challenges: Building Digital Readiness Despite the clear benefits of AI and digital tools, the road to digital transformation for SMEs is not without its challenges. Digital adoption among SMEs in Abu Dhabi has been slower than expected, due to factors such as limited digital literacy, budget constraints, and resistance to change. </p><p>For AI and digital tools to truly transform SMEs, there must be a concerted effort from both the government and private sectors to support digital literacy, foster innovation, and provide resources that encourage digital adoption. Government initiatives in Abu Dhabi, such as the Smart Abu Dhabi initiative and the Digital Transformation Strategy, are playing a critical role in addressing these challenges. By offering grants, training programs, and innovation hubs, the government is enabling SMEs to access the tools and knowledge needed to integrate AI and digital technologies effectively. At the same time, private sector players and technology providers must also invest in building tailored solutions for SMEs that are both affordable and scalable. For many SMEs, the cost of implementing AI and digital tools remains a significant barrier. However, through affordable Software as a Service (SaaS) models and subscription-based solutions, SMEs can access the latest technologies without the hefty capital expenditure. </p><p>AI and Digital Tools as Enablers of a Resilient Future Looking ahead, AI and digital tools will not just be catalysts for growth—they will be essential for building resilience in Abu Dhabi’s SME sector. In a world where economic uncertainties, global competition, and technological disruption are constants, SMEs that embrace AI and digital tools will be better equipped to adapt to changing market conditions, seize new opportunities, and thrive in an increasingly digital-first world. In conclusion, while the journey toward full digital transformation may be challenging, AI and digital tools are no longer optional—they are critical enablers of business growth and sustainability. SMEs in Abu Dhabi that can harness the power of these technologies will not only stay competitive—they will help shape the future of the economy. </p><p>The future of SMEs in Abu Dhabi is digital, intelligent, and agile. AI and digital tools are fundamentally altering the business landscape, offering new opportunities for growth, innovation, and competitiveness. By embracing these technologies, SMEs in Abu Dhabi can not only improve operational efficiency but also position themselves as leaders in the future economy. The time to act is now—those who adapt early will lead the charge in creating a more innovative, resilient, and digitally connected economy.</p>	AI and digital tools are reshaping SME operations, models, and competitiveness.	{Article,Knowledge,"Technology & Innovation"}	https://timesofdubai.ae/wp-content/uploads/2025/05/1745384990598.webp	0	0	{"body_json": {"type": "doc", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"text": "The emergence of artificial intelligence (AI) and digital tools is reshaping the landscape of small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) worldwide. In Abu Dhabi, a city known for its forward-thinking policies and rapid economic transformation, these technological advancements are not merely trends—they are the driving force behind the next wave of SME evolution. While larger corporations have long benefited from AI and digital tools, SMEs in Abu Dhabi are now starting to realize the immense potential of these technologies in driving innovation, improving efficiency, and scaling operations. AI and digital tools are no longer just “nice-to-have” for SMEs—they are strategic imperatives for staying competitive in an increasingly globalized and tech-driven market. Yet, as transformative as these tools are, the real question is: ", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "blockquote", "content": [{"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"text": "How are SMEs in Abu Dhabi truly harnessing these innovations?", "type": "text"}]}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "content": [{"text": "In this article, we explore how AI and digital tools are not just enhancing the capabilities of SMEs but fundamentally transforming the way they operate, innovate, and grow